= General Concepts
#v(15pt)
The concept of swing is frequently treated in music pedagogy as an ineffable quality of performance — an experiential phenomenon resistant to precise definition and accessible primarily through imitation and prolonged stylistic immersion. The present course proposes an alternative framework: a generalized, formally grounded theory of swing in which the phenomenon is defined not as a stylistic attribute but as a structural property of rhythmic subdivision. The central claim is that swing arises whenever the subdivision grid of a beat is distorted such that its constituent intervals become unequal. This deceptively simple observation serves as the generative principle from which a comprehensive theoretical apparatus is derived — encompassing the characterization of subdivision patterns as sequences of long and short values, the formalization of swing as a continuous ratio parameter, the tempo-dependence of swing range, and the critical distinction between functional rhythmic reality and its notational representation. The present chapter establishes the foundational vocabulary and conceptual premises upon which all subsequent developments in this course depend.
